100 Years Ago Today, This is What Was Happening ...

On January 24, 1926, the British government announced a significant reduction in coal production to combat the ongoing miners' strike, which has gripped the nation. In the United States, President Calvin Coolidge addressed the need for improved infrastructure, emphasizing the importance of a robust economy. Meanwhile, tensions continued to rise in the Middle East as the League of Nations prepared to discuss mandates in the region, highlighting the shifting dynamics post-World War I.
